# Svelte Layer Conventions

- Svelte 5 runes only: `$state`, `$derived`, `$effect`, `$props`. No legacy
  stores or `export let`.
- Get the shared engine via `getEngine()` from `src/lib/engine/context.ts`.
  Never instantiate `PresentationEngine` in a layer (only the root page does).
- Components are presentational: read `$derived` engine state and render. Keep
  presentation logic in the engine.

## Bridging to imperative libraries (PixiJS / Reveal.js)

Push reactive state into imperative APIs inside `$effect`, and always tear down
in `onDestroy`.

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  const engine = getEngine();
  $effect(() => {
    void engine.currentSlide;   // track dependency
    deck?.slide(engine.currentSlide, 0);
  });
  onDestroy(() => deck?.destroy());
</script>
```

### Reveal.js only renders sections it has registered

Scenario content loads asynchronously, so the deck usually initializes with an
EMPTY `<div class="slides">`. Reveal hides every `<section>` it has not tagged
`present/past/future`, so slides added reactively afterwards stay invisible. When
the slide set changes you MUST re-register them:

```svelte
$effect(() => {
  const count = slides.length;          // track the set
  const index = engine.currentSlide;
  if (!ready || !deck) return;
  void (async () => {
    await tick();                        // flush {#each} into the DOM first
    if (count !== syncedCount) { deck.sync(); syncedCount = count; }
    deck.slide(index, 0);
  })();
});
```

Calling `deck.slide()` alone is not enough on a freshly loaded/changed deck.

## Mobile + RTL

- Mobile-first; the app is framed as a phone. Avoid desktop-only assumptions.
- The document is RTL (`dir="rtl"`). Wrap LTR fragments such as numeric counters
  with `dir="ltr"` to avoid bidi reordering (e.g. `2 / 5`).
